The first step in analyzing the shock ramp simulation is processing the raw hdf5 files with:

/Users/trevorreed/UVA_postdoc_stuff/gparc/data/shock_ramp/dynamic_mesh_reader_physical_space.py

This outputs a single pt with all of the relevant info to continue.
Then use extract_dmr_boundaries.py in utils/ to read from one of the hdf5 "map" files.
This file extracts the physical shock ramp boundaries and saves that info to utils/wedge_mesh_spec.pt

Before getting to mesh prediction, I first need to define the physical boundaries of the system;
for shock ramp, the physical boundaries do not follow a rectangular space.
I can do this with utils/extract_dmr_boundaries.py, which produces a file, wedge_mesh_spec.pt, from any one of the .map.hdf5 for the relevant simulation.
This file should be specified in the config file under:
"mesh": {
    "starting_mesh_path":

With the above steps complete, I can move to the mesh prediction. This can be done by running the main file,
train.py, with "precomp_force_recompute": true in the config file under "train". This automatically
runs the training after the mesh prediction and interpolation steps have completed. 
An h5 file with the info from the pre-training steps is saved to cache/, with the
name specified by "precomp_cache_path": under "train" in the config file. 

The training can be run again without the pre-training steps by setting "precomp_force_recompute": false
in the config file. This will read from the saved h5 file in cache.  
